  implications for OPINION/2026/017 (flagged for Mrs. Ndhlovu review, not adjudicated by worker):
    1. ABSENCE of a ToS on a WordPress site that hosts authoritative government judicial content is itself a material data point. For a typical commercial website, absence of a ToS is a meaningful fair-dealing fact because no contractual terms restrict the scraper/reader. For a government-adjacent content host, the analysis is different — the content is of state authorship/publication, and the default copyright regime is the Copyright and Performance Rights Act, Cap. 406, as amended by Act No. 25 of 2010. Crown/state copyright interacts with fair dealing under s.21 of Cap. 406; the absence of a contractual overlay on the hosting site means the analysis collapses back to statute.
    2. The only explicit restriction we have found on the entire site relating to reproduction of judgments is the CouncilofLaw Reporting copyright notice QUOTED in J-POL-3 OBS-1, which appears PER-POST on the judgment stub pages, not as a site-wide ToS. It is a copyright assertion, not a contract. This is a narrower posture than a site-wide terms-of-use contract would be.
    3. Disqus tracking + no consent banner + no privacy policy is NOT a copyright fact but IS a data-protection fact. If OPINION/017 is strictly copyright/fair-dealing scoped, this is out of scope for /017; if there is a companion OPINION track on data-protection posture, this should be surfaced there too.
    4. The "© 2016" footer is evidence of configuration neglect rather than affirmative policy design. The site was set up in 2016 (which matches the /wp-content/uploads/2016/09/blank-supremecourt-decision.jpg placeholder image date from J-POL-3) and has never been legally re-papered. Mrs. Ndhlovu may want this narrative for the opinion's "site posture" section.
    5. The per-post Council of Law Reporting notice is therefore the ONLY contractual/policy restriction that attaches to any individual judgment PDF. It is consistent across posts (not a one-off; it appears on this post and plausibly on all SC-Decisions-category posts — J-POL-3b did not re-walk to verify this across multiple posts, but could do so cheaply within budget if instructed).

